  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous statutes that address money laundering at both the national and international levels. In the United States, the primary legislation targeting money laundering is the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970**, along with subsequent amendments and related laws. Here are some key statutes and frameworks:\n\n### United States\n1. **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)**  \n   - Requires financial institutions to report certain transactions, maintain records, and implement anti-money laundering (AML) programs.  \n   - Includes requirements for filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs) and Currency Transaction Reports (CTRs).  \n\n2. **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA) of 1986**  \n   - Makes money laundering a federal crime.  \n   - Prohibits knowingly engaging in financial transactions involving proceeds from unlawful activities.  \n\n3. **USA PATRIOT Act of 2001**  \n   - Strengthened AML provisions by enhancing due diligence requirements for financial institutions.  \n   - Expanded the scope of reporting and monitoring, including provisions for correspondent banking and foreign accounts.  \n\n4. **Anti-Money Laundering Act (AMLA) of 2020**  \n   - Modernized AML laws, including the establishment of a beneficial ownership registry to combat shell companies.  \n   - Increased penalties for violations and expanded oversight of cryptocurrencies.  \n\n### International Frameworks\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**  \n   - An intergovernmental organization that sets global standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and related threats.  \n   - Publishes recommendations that countries are encouraged to implement.  \n\n2. **United Nations Conventions**  \n   - The **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** addresses money laundering related to drug trafficking.  \n   - The **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** includes provisions to combat money laundering associated with organized crime.  \n\n### European Union\n1. **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**  \n   - A series of directives that harmonize AML laws across EU member states.  \n   - The latest, **AMLD6**, focuses on strengthening AML measures and combating terrorist financing.  \n\nThese statutes and frameworks aim to prevent criminals from disguising the illicit origins of their funds, thereby disrupting illegal activities and protecting the integrity of financial systems. Financial institutions, businesses, and individuals are required to comply with these laws to detect and report suspicious activities.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
